'''Benjamin Craig Old''' (born 13 August 2002) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] for {{French football updater|Saint-Étienne}} club [[AS Saint-Étienne|Saint-Étienne]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].<ref name="debut">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Academy player Ben Old makes Wellington Phoenix debut in front of 24,105 people |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/125218879/academy-player-ben-old-makes-wellington-phoenix-debut-in-front-of-24105-people |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=23 May 2021 |language=en |archive-date=25 May 2021 |access-date=25 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210525222004/https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/125218879/academy-player-ben-old-makes-wellington-phoenix-debut-in-front-of-24105-people |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Early life ==
Old began his sports career as a golfer; he was given his first [[golf club]] when he was two.<ref name="prodigy"/> Old was considered a former child golf prodigy, playing in his first international golf tournament at the age of seven. He had travelled to the United States to play against other child prodigies from around the world in [[Shadow Creek Golf Course|Las Vegas]], [[Pinehurst Resort|Pinehurst]] and [[Torrey Pines Golf Course|San Diego]].<ref name="prodigy">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Former child golf prodigy Ben Old striving towards Wellington Phoenix contract |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/124058745/former-child-golf-prodigy-ben-old-striving-towards-wellington-phoenix-contract |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=31 January 2021 |language=en}}</ref>

== Club career ==
=== Wellington Phoenix ===
Old originally lived in Auckland before he moved to Wellington and joined the Wellington Phoenix Football Academy in 2018.<ref name="prodigy"/> While not an official member of Wellington Phoenix's senior squad, Old had trained with the team before they went to Australia.<ref name="prodigy"/> Old joined the team again for training when they returned, making his debut as a substitute in the Phoenix's 3–0 win over [[Western United FC|Western United]] and [[Nutmeg (association football)|nutmegging]] his defender with his first touch.<ref name="home">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Ben Old feeling more at home with Wellington Phoenix after surprise debut |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/125236020/ben-old-feeling-more-at-home-with-wellington-phoenix-after-surprise-debut |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=25 May 2021 |language=en |archive-date=25 May 2021 |access-date=25 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210525222004/https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/125236020/ben-old-feeling-more-at-home-with-wellington-phoenix-after-surprise-debut |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="debut"/>

Old scored his first goal for the Wellington Phoenix during a 3–0 victory over the [[Brisbane Roar]] on 30 March 2022.<ref name="goal">{{cite press release |author=[[Wellington Phoenix FC]] |title=Men's match review: Wellington Phoenix vs. Brisbane Roar |url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/mens-match-review-wellington-phoenix-vs-brisbane-roar-3 |publisher=Wellington Phoenix FC |date=31 March 2022 |language=en |access-date=31 March 2022 |archive-date=2 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221002154542/https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/mens-match-review-wellington-phoenix-vs-brisbane-roar-3 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Saint-Étienne ===

On 9 July 2024, Old signed for [[Ligue 1]] club [[AS Saint-Étienne|Saint-Étienne]] on a four-year contract with an option for a fifth year.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ben Old rejoint l'AS Saint-Étienne ! |url=https://www.asse.fr/fr/actualites/ben-old-rejoint-l-as-saint-etienne--ac36847 |access-date=28 July 2024 |date=9 July 2024 |publisher=[[AS Saint-Étienne]] |language=fr |archive-date=22 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240722102643/https://www.asse.fr/fr/actualites/ben-old-rejoint-l-as-saint-etienne--ac36847 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 17 August 2024, Old played his first game with Saint-Étienne, a 0-1 defeat against [[AS Monaco FC]] in the first day of the [[2024–25 Ligue 1]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Monaco 1-0 ASSE, Ligue 1 |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/match-direct/ligue-1/2024-2025/monaco-asse-live/655862 |website=L’Équipe |access-date=6 April 2025}}</ref> becoming the first New Zealander to start a game in [[Ligue 1]], and the second to even play.{{efn|after [[Bill Tuiloma]] in [[2014–15 Ligue 1|2015]] with [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Ben Old, un Néo-Zélandais sur le green |url=https://www.sofoot.com/articles/ligue-1-portrait-de-ben-old-le-joueur-neo-zelandais-de-las-saint-etienne |website=So Foot |date=20 September 2024 |access-date=6 April 2025}}</ref>

On 13 September 2024, he played his third Ligue 1 game, a 1-0 win against [[Lille OSC|Lille]],<ref>{{cite web |title=ASSE 1-0 Lille, Ligue 1 |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/match-direct/ligue-1/2024-2025/asse-lille-live/655891 |website=L’Équipe |access-date=6 April 2024}}</ref> beating [[Bill Tuiloma|Bill Tuiloma’s]] tally of two games and setting a new record for a New Zealander in Ligue 1.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bill Tuiloma : « Portland, c'est un peu l'OM de la MLS » |url=https://www.sofoot.com/articles/bill-tuiloma-portland-cest-un-peu-lom-de-la-mls |website=So Foot |date=8 November 2018 |access-date=6 April 2025}}</ref>

== International career ==
=== New Zealand U-17s ===
Old was part of the [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand U-17]] team that won the [[2018 OFC U-16 Championship]] and qualified for [[2019 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA U-17 World Cup 2019 – News – History for Solomons, New Zealand continue run |url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/news/history-made-as-solomons-reach-world-stage |website=[[FIFA]] |access-date=25 May 2021 |archive-date=25 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210525215122/https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/news/history-made-as-solomons-reach-world-stage |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U-17 players looking to impress |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/78339 |website=[[New Zealand Football]] |access-date=25 May 2021 |archive-date=25 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210525214853/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/78339 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Figueira names quality World Cup squad |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/82384 |website=[[New Zealand Football]] |access-date=25 May 2021 |archive-date=25 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210525214849/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/82384 |url-status=live }}</ref> Old played in two games at the World Cup, first coming on as a sub in New Zealand's opening 1–2 loss to [[Angola national under-17 football team|Angola]] before getting a start in the team's 1–0 win over [[Canada national under-17 football team|Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA U-17 World Cup Brazil 2019 – Matches – New Zealand – Angola |url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/match/400079802/#match-lineups |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924130316/https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/match/400079802/#match-lineups |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 September 2019 |website=[[FIFA]] |access-date=25 May 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA U-17 World Cup Brazil 2019 – Matches – Canada – New Zealand |url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/match/400079805/#match-lineups |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924130347/https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/match/400079805/#match-lineups |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 September 2019 |website=[[FIFA]] |access-date=25 May 2021}}</ref>

=== Olympic Games ===
On 25 June 2021, he was named in [[New Zealand men's national under-23 football team|New Zealand]] [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's team squads|reserve squad]] for the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020
Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Squads named for Tokyo 2020 |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622 |website=NZ Football |access-date=21 September 2024 |archive-date=25 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210625021412/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>
Though he was actually travelled to Japan, he didn't play any game.

=== New Zealand ===
Old was named in the 30-man [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|2022 FIFA World Cup Oceania qualifiers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Squad named for FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022 Oceania Qualifiers |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/113121?newsfeedId=1230159 |website=[[New Zealand Football]] |date=8 March 2022 |access-date=31 March 2022 |archive-date=31 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331172125/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/113121?newsfeedId=1230159 |url-status=live }}</ref> He subsequently made his international debut on 19 March 2022, coming on as a substitute in the 67th minute during New Zealand's 1–0 victory against [[Papua New Guinea national football team|Papua New Guinea]] in the group stage.<ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022™ |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/qatar2022/qualifiers/ofc/match-center/400214345 |website=[[FIFA]] |access-date=31 March 2022 |archive-date=29 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220329075512/https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/qatar2022/qualifiers/ofc/match-center/400214345 |url-status=live }}</ref>

